<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920225-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>920225-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.:   Company Uses Bank Loans   To Repurchase Junk Bonds</HL><DATE>02/25/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   RN</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><NS>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, REPURCHASES, SWAPS (BBK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. took another step to lightenits debt load, using low-cost bank loans to retire nearly $1billion of junk bonds yielding an average of 14.9%.   The bonds were repurchased in a privately negotiatedtransaction at a significant premium to their current bookvalue. As a result, RJR Nabisco said, it will incur a $160million extraordinary charge in its first-quarter results.</LP><TEXT>   RJR said, however, that the repurchase would be&quot;advantageous for shareholders in terms of both future cashflow and earnings.&quot; The New York-based tobacco and foodcompany currently is able to borrow from banks under afive-year loan facility at about a 5% interest rate. RJR'soverall average borrowing cost is about 10.5%.   The bonds repurchased are $750 million principal amount ofzero coupon bonds due 2001, $165 million of 15% bonds due2001, and $85 million of 13.5% bonds due 2001. All threeclasses of bonds were created when RJR Nabisco underwent aleveraged buyout in 1989. The zero coupon bonds, which don'tpay cash interest for several years, have an accreted value,or current book value, of $550 million.   RJR declined to say whether the bonds were sold by a majorinstitution or by a Wall Street firm that had rounded them upfrom its customers. RJR did say that the transaction wasinitiated by the seller.</TEXT></DOC>